iant of   Keighley  ."]},{"name":"Keigley","meanings":["Altered form of English   Keighley  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":30,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Henry I Keighley MP was born in 1260, in Keighley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Richard II de Kighley, was 38 and his mother, Katherine Keighley, was 27. He married Ellen le Boteler in January 1285. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1314, in Keighley, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1260–1314":"1260–1314","1260–1301":"1260–1301","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","–1330":"–1330","–1334":"–1334","–1356":"–1356","–1366":"–1366","1223–1285":"1223–1285","1233–Female":"1233–Surnud","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1330":"1330","1285":"1285","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1314":"1314","1301":"1301","1356":"1356","1334":"1334","1223":"1223","1366":"1366","1233":"1233","by 1285   1st wife":"jaanuar 1285","alive 1285  ":"1285","Keighley, Yorkshire, England":"Keighley, Yorkshire, England","Keighley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Keighley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1260–1314":"1260–1314","1260–1301":"1260–1301","1270–Female":"12